    ]
  })} />

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-bg"></div>
    <div class="container hero-content">
      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a> &rarr; <a href="/trucking-insurance-idaho/">Idaho Trucking Insurance</a> &rarr; Chain Laws
      </nav>
      <h1>Idaho Chain Laws for Truckers</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Complete Guide to Idaho Code 49-948</p>
      <p class="hero-intro">Idaho's chain law is targeted, not blanket. Chains are only required on <strong>three specific mountain passes</strong>, only when ITD posts them, and with <strong>more exemptions than most truckers realize</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THREE PASSES -->
  <section class="passes">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">Where Chain Laws Apply</span>
        <h2>The Three Passes Where Chain Laws Apply</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">Idaho Code 49-948 limits chain requirements to these mountain passes only. These are the ONLY three locations where Idaho can legally require chains - other highways do not have chain requirements regardless of weather.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="passes-grid">
        <div class="pass-card">
          <h3>1. Lookout Pass</h3>
          <span class="pass-route">Interstate 90</span>
          <table class="pass-details">
            <tr><td>Location</td><td>Idaho-Montana border at mile marker 0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Elevation</td><td>4,725 feet</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Route</td><td>I-90 near Mullan, Idaho</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Conditions</td><td>Heavy snow November-March; frequent chain controls</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chain-up area</td><td>Eastbound before summit climb</td></tr>
          </table>
          <p class="pass-note">Lookout Pass is the highest and most frequently chained of Idaho's three passes. If you're running I-90 east toward Montana in winter, expect chain controls here.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pass-card">
          <h3>2. Fourth of July Pass</h3>
          <span class="pass-route">Interstate 90</span>
          <table class="pass-details">
            <tr><td>Location</td><td>Between Coeur d'Alene and Kellogg</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Elevation</td><td>3,081 feet</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Route</td><td>I-90</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Conditions</td><td>Lower elevation but steep grades; chains during storms</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chain-up area</td><td>Designated pull-outs on both approaches</td></tr>
          </table>
          <p class="pass-note">Fourth of July Pass sits lower than Lookout but has grades that catch trucks in icy conditions. Both passes are often posted simultaneously during winter storms.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pass-card">
          <h3>3. Lolo Pass</h3>
          <span class="pass-route">US Highway 12</span>
          <table class="pass-details">
            <tr><td>Location</td><td>Idaho-Montana border on Lewis and Clark Highway</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Elevation</td><td>5,233 feet</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Route</td><td>US Highway 12</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Conditions</td><td>Remote; limited services; rapid weather changes</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chain-up area</td><td>Limited pull-outs; chain up in Kooskia or Lowell when possible</td></tr>
          </table>
          <p class="pass-note">Lolo Pass is the highest and most remote of the three. If you're hauling over Highway 12, plan to be self-sufficient - services are sparse and conditions can deteriorate without warning.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="critical-note">
        <strong>Critical point:</strong> These are the ONLY three locations where Idaho can legally require chains. Other highways - including I-84, I-86, and I-15 - do not have chain requirements under Idaho Code 49-948, regardless of weather.
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHEN REQUIRED -->
  <section class="when-required">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">When Chains Are Required</span>
        <h2>How Chain Controls Work</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="content-block">
        <p>ITD determines when conditions warrant mandatory chains. Under Idaho Code 49-948, before chains can be required:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Multiple advance notices</strong> must be posted (signs, variable message boards)</li>
          <li><strong>Adequate pull-out areas</strong> must be provided for chaining up</li>
          <li><strong>Chains cannot be required on bare pavement</strong> - if the road is clear, chains cannot be mandated</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="conditions-check">
        <h3>How to Check Conditions Before You Roll</h3>
        <table class="resource-table">
          <tr><td>Idaho 511</td><td><a href="https://511.idaho.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">511.idaho.gov</a></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Phone</td><td>511 (in-state) or 1-888-432-7623</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ITD Cameras</td><td>Live feeds at 511.idaho.gov</td></tr>
        </table>
        <p class="check-note">Check conditions before committing to a pass crossing. Weather on Idaho's mountain passes can change from clear to chain-required within hours.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMERCIAL REQUIREMENTS -->
  <section class="requirements">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">Idaho Code 49-948(2)</span>
        <h2>Commercial Vehicle Chain Requirements</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">When chains are posted, commercial vehicles must meet these minimum standards:</p>
      </div>

      <div class="req-grid">
        <div class="req-card">
          <h3>On the Tractor/Power Unit</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>At least <strong>one tire chained on each side</strong> of <strong>one drive axle</strong></li>
            <li>Minimum: <strong>2 chains</strong> on the power unit</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="req-card">
          <h3>On Each Towed Vehicle (Trailer)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>At least <strong>one axle chained at or near the rear</strong> of each towed vehicle</li>
            <li>One tire per side of that axle</li>
            <li>Minimum: <strong>2 chains per trailer</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="config-table">
        <h3>In Practice</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Configuration</th><th>Minimum Chains Required</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Straight truck</td><td>2 (both sides of one drive axle)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tractor-trailer</td><td>4 (2 drive + 2 trailer rear)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Doubles</td><td>6 (2 drive + 2 per trailer)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="practical-advice"><strong>Practical advice:</strong> Carry more chains than the legal minimum. Chains break. Conditions on Lookout Pass can deteriorate fast. Having chains for both drive axles gives you backup.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- EXEMPTIONS -->
  <section class="exemptions">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">Idaho Code 49-948(6)</span>
        <h2>Complete List of Exemptions</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">Idaho law exempts these vehicles from chain requirements <strong>even when chains are posted</strong>:</p>
      </div>

      <div class="exempt-grid">
        <div class="exempt-category">
          <h3>Government and Emergency Vehicles</h3>
          <table>
            <tr><td>State transportation maintenance vehicles</td><td>ITD snowplows, sanders, maintenance trucks</td></tr>
            <tr><td>School buses</td><td>Any vehicle operating as a school bus</td></tr>
            <tr><td>U.S. Mail vehicles</td><td>Postal Service and contracted mail carriers</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Wrecker/tow trucks</td><td>Recovery vehicles responding to calls</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="exempt-category highlight">
          <h3>Agricultural Exemptions</h3>
          <table>
            <tr><td>Farm equipment transport</td><td>Trucks hauling tractors, implements, farm machinery</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Agricultural product haulers</td><td>Grain, produce, livestock, hay, feed - any ag commodity</td></tr>
          </table>
          <p class="exempt-note"><strong>This is significant for Idaho truckers.</strong> Agriculture is a major industry in Idaho, and the chain law exemption covers both owner-operators hauling their own products AND commercial ag carriers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="exempt-category">
          <h3>Natural Resource Exemptions</h3>
          <table>
            <tr><td>Forest product carriers</td><td>Logs, lumber, pulpwood, wood chips, forest products</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Mining product carriers</td><td>Sand, gravel, aggregates, ore, mining products</td></tr>
          </table>
          <p class="exempt-note">Chip trucks running to mills and aggregate haulers for construction are specifically exempt from chain requirements.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="exemption-meaning">
        <h3>What Exemption Means (and Doesn't Mean)</h3>
        <div class="meaning-grid">
          <div class="meaning-card yes">
            <strong>Exemption means:</strong>
            <p>You're not legally required to chain up when controls are posted.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="meaning-card no">
            <strong>Exemption does NOT mean:</strong>
            <p>Chaining up is prohibited. If conditions are severe on Lolo Pass, chains are still a smart call regardless of your exemption status. The exemption protects you from citation - it doesn't protect you from physics.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- VIOLATIONS -->
  <section class="violations">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">Consequences</span>
        <h2>Violations and Consequences</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="content-block">
        <p>Idaho Code 49-948 doesn't specify exact fine amounts - penalties are set by local courts as misdemeanor infractions.</p>

        <h3>If caught without chains when required:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Citation for violation of Idaho Code 49-948</li>
          <li>Misdemeanor traffic infraction with court-set fine</li>
          <li>Delay while you chain up before proceeding</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>If an incident occurs due to operating without required chains:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Full liability for damage and injuries</li>
          <li>Insurance complications if you violated posted requirements</li>
          <li>CSA points if incident triggers roadside inspection</li>
          <li>Potential cargo claims if delivery is delayed or damaged</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="real-cost">
          <strong>The real cost:</strong> Getting stuck on Lookout Pass isn't just a ticket. It's hours of delay, potential tow fees ($500+ for a commercial vehicle), and missed delivery windows. Chains cost $200. One stuck truck costs far more.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PRACTICAL TIPS -->
  <section class="tips">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">Practical Advice</span>
        <h2>Practical Tips for Idaho Mountain Pass Operations</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="tips-grid">
        <div class="tip-card">
          <h3>Before Winter Season</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Test your chains</strong> on your truck before you need them</li>
            <li>Carry chains for all required axles <strong>plus spares</strong></li>
            <li>Keep chain binders, tensioners, and work gloves accessible</li>
            <li>Consider a headlamp - chain-up areas are often dark</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="tip-card">
          <h3>At the Chain-Up Area</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Use designated pull-outs only - don't chain on the shoulder</li>
            <li>Allow 20-30 minutes for a full chain-up in cold conditions</li>
            <li>Check tension after the first mile - chains loosen</li>
            <li>Remove chains as soon as you're clear of the chain zone</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="tip-card">
          <h3>Route Planning</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Check 511.idaho.gov before departing</li>
            <li>Build buffer time when crossing passes in winter</li>
            <li>Know where chain-up areas are BEFORE you reach them</li>
            <li>Have a backup plan if passes close</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="tip-card">
          <h3>Equipment Recommendations</h3>
          <table>
            <tr><td>Chain type</td><td>Single-wheel chains for standard use; cross-chains for severe conditions</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Spares</td><td>Minimum 2 extra chains - they break at the worst times</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tools</td><td>Chain tensioners, bungee cords, heavy gloves</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Visibility</td><td>Headlamp or flashlight for dark chain-up operations</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- QUICK REFERENCE -->
  <section class="quick-ref">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header centered">
        <span class="section-tag">Summary</span>
        <h2>Idaho Chain Law Quick Reference</h2>
      </div>

      <table class="summary-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Topic</th><th>Statute</th><th>Summary</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Where required</td><td>49-948</td><td>Lookout Pass, Fourth of July Pass, Lolo Pass only</td></tr>
          <tr><td>When required</td><td>49-948</td><td>When ITD posts; cannot require on bare pavement</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Commercial requirements</td><td>49-948(2)</td><td>One drive axle + rear of each trailer</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Exemptions</td><td>49-948(6)</td><td>Ag, forest products, mining, mail, school buses, tow trucks</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- INSURANCE CTA -->
  <section class="insurance-cta">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Need Idaho Trucking Insurance?</h2>
      <p>RMS Truck Insurance covers owner-operators and small fleets running Idaho's mountain passes. We know the difference between hauling logs over Lolo Pass and running produce on I-84 - and we understand which operations are exempt from chain laws.</p>

      <div class="cta-actions">
